      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">In the aftermath of a disaster, various health issues often emerge due to the disruption of normal living conditions and services. In the post-disaster phase, public health professionals monitor and respond to a range of health concerns. Based on historical data and common occurrences, which is the most commonly reported disease in the post-disaster phase?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q8170752",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 34715,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        7
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Ans. C. Gastroenteritis</strong></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option C.</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Gastroenteritis (Typhoid, cholera)&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>is frequently reported in the <strong>post-disaster phase</strong>. <strong>Disasters</strong>, especially after <strong>natural</strong> ones like <strong>floods and earthquakes</strong>, often lead to the <strong>contamination</strong> of <strong>water supplies</strong> and compromised <strong>sanitation facilities</strong>.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">The <strong>increased risk </strong>of <strong>gastroenteritis</strong> after disasters is a significant public health concern, necessitating <strong>prompt</strong> and <strong>effective </strong>response measures to <strong>prevent and control outbreaks</strong>.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option A. Respiratory Infections:</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Incorrect,</strong> although <strong>common</strong>, <strong>respiratory infections</strong> are <strong>not</strong> typically the <strong>most reported disease</strong> in <strong>post-disaster settings</strong>.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option B. Malaria:&nbsp;Incorrect</strong>, malaria may increase in certain post-disaster situations, particularly where standing water increases, but it is not the most commonly reported.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option D. Cholera</strong>:&nbsp;<strong>Incorrect,</strong> while cholera <strong>outbreaks </strong>can occur <strong>post-disaster</strong>, especially in <strong>flood-affected areas, gastroenteritis</strong> is more <strong>commonly</strong> <strong>reported overall.</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Gastroenteritis (Typhoid, cholera)&nbsp;</strong>is the <strong>most commonly</strong> reported disease in the <strong>post-disaster</strong> <strong>phase.</strong> This emphasizes the importance of <strong>ensuring clean water supply</strong> and <strong>proper sanitation</strong> in <strong>disaster-affected areas</strong> to <strong>prevent</strong> the <strong>spread</strong> of <strong>diseases</strong> associated with <strong>contaminated water</strong> and <strong>poor hygiene</strong>.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Reference: Park 26<sup>th</sup> ed 892</strong></span></p>",
